  "slug": "hunters-chicken",
  "title": "Hunter's Chicken",
  "subtitle": "Chicken breast wrapped in streaky bacon with a smoky tomato sauce and melted Cheddar",
  "excerpt": "Hunter's chicken is a British pub kitchen staple: chicken breast wrapped in streaky bacon, baked in a smoky tomato sauce, and finished with melted Cheddar on top. It takes 40 minutes in the oven and produces exactly what you expect: a generous, satisfying plate.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Contemporary British pub cooking. A staple of British chain restaurant menus from the 1990s onwards. Named loosely after the French 'chasseur' (hunter's) sauce tradition, though the British version is a distinct and simpler dish.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Hunter's chicken",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpdr5cyt0000gsv4eak355le"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " is straightforward. The only technique worth noting is wrapping: the bacon must overlap around the chicken breast tightly enough that it does not unravel in the oven. Secure each one with a cocktail stick if needed, removing before serving.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "smoked paprika",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpdr5czh0001gsv4dfjstifi"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " is what gives the sauce its defining character. Make the sauce before the chicken goes in; it needs 15 minutes on its own to develop flavour before it becomes a baking medium.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
