        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make the sauce",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{olive-oil}} of olive oil",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " in a frying pan over medium heat. Fry the onion for 5 minutes until soft. Add garlic and ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{smoked-paprika}}",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and cook for 1 minute. Add ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{tomato-puree}} of tomato purée",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and stir for 1 minute. Add ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{tinned-tomatoes}} of tinned tomatoes",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ", ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{worcestershire-sauce}}",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{caster-sugar}} of sugar",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ". Simmer for 15 minutes until thick. Season with ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{sea-salt-flakes}}",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{black-pepper}}",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ".",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Wrap and bake",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the oven to 200°C (180°C fan). Wrap each ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{chicken-breast}} chicken breast",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " tightly with ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{streaky-bacon}} of streaky bacon",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " (3-4 rashers per breast). Spoon the tomato sauce into a roasting dish. Nestle the wrapped chicken breasts in the sauce. Bake for 25-30 minutes until the chicken is cooked through (internal temperature 75°C). Scatter ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{cheddar}} of grated Cheddar",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " over the top and return to the oven for 5 minutes until melted and bubbling. Rest for 5 minutes before serving.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "rows": [
            {
              "fix": "Wrap tightly and place seam-side down in the dish. Use cocktail sticks to secure if needed.",
              "cause": "Rashers not wrapped tightly enough, or chicken placed in sauce without seam-side down",
              "symptom": "Bacon falls away from the chicken during baking"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Check the internal temperature at 25 minutes. Large breasts can be pounded to an even thickness before wrapping for more even cooking.",
              "cause": "Overcooked, or large breasts were not butterflied to an even thickness",
              "symptom": "Chicken is dry"
            },
            {
              "fix": "The sauce needs 15 minutes of simmering to cook out the tinned tomato sharpness and develop flavour. Do not skip this step.",
              "cause": "Sauce was not simmered long enough before the chicken was added",
              "symptom": "Sauce tastes raw or sharp"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Grate finely and scatter in an even layer. Return to the oven at a higher temperature (200°C) if the cheese is slow to melt.",
              "cause": "Scattered too thickly in places, or oven too cool",
              "symptom": "Cheese does not melt evenly"
            }
          ]
        },
        "content": []
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Hunter's chicken is a British creation despite the name. It appeared on chain restaurant menus in the 1990s and became a staple of pub food culture: reliable, filling, and familiar. At home it is a useful weeknight dish because the sauce can be made in advance and the assembly is simple. Serve with chips, mashed potato, or a plain green salad.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
